\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rough outline of the protocol is quite simple:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
initial authentication messages are POSTed to an agreed-upon or indicated
 resource...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
....which then results in a new resource being created with the authentication
 reply message as the new resource's representation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Thereafter any additional authentication message exchanges needed (for multi-leg
ged mechanisms) are POSTed to the new resource creating additional resources.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The resource created by the POSTing of the initial authentication mechanism
 identifies the resulting session, and its URI is known as the session URI.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Session URIs can be used to multiplex multiple sessions over the same TCP/TLS
 connections, implement logout, and share sessions across multiple related
 servers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Server-initiated authentication is also possible, whereby the server sends
 a challenge in 401 errors in headers.
 If the server gives the client a choice of mechanisms (multiple WWW-Authenticat
e header values) and the client picks one where the server sent a challenge,
 then the client consumes that message and POSTs subsequent ones to the
 indicated URI.
\end_layout

