\begin_layout Section
API-Imposed Constraints
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To the extent that existing Application Programming Interfaces (APIs) assume
 specific styles of HTTP authentication message flows, if we want those
 APIs to support RESTauth backwards-compatibly, then those APIs may impose
 constraints on RESTauth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, the Android Account Manager API assumes a single round trip
 for authentication.
 But the Android Account Manager could perform all but the last round trip
 on behalf of the application, then let the application perform the last
 round trip.
 In order for that to work we need the authentication message exchange to
 be orthogonal to TCP/TLS connections -- that is, we need it to be possible
 to use multiple TCP/TLS connections for completing a single authentication
 exchange.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A typical constraining characteristic might be that an API assumes the use
 of GET with tokens encoded into the URI, or that the API makes no room
 for the use of headers in authentication message exchanges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One way to work around such constraints may be to provide various options
 in this framework.
 Another might be to use OAuth 1.0 
\begin_inset Flex EntityXRef
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
RFC5849
\end_layout

\end_inset

 or 2.0 
\begin_inset Flex EntityXRef
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I-D.ietf-oauth-v2
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as a bridge: the API would use this framework under the covers then obtain
 OAuth credentials from the server that the application can then use in
 any way that the API's form allows for.
\end_layout

